How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]The ever versatile VLC can do a lot of things. Screen recording is one of them. https://itsfoss.com/vlc-record-screen/ 650a776dbb002c9598310f15VLCSreenath Wed, 11 Oct 2023 02:58:43 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/record-screen-with-vlc.png" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]"><p> VLC is more than just a video player. It&#39;s a versatile video tool with so many features that a normal user could never know them.</p><p> You can <a href="https://itsfoss.com/download-youtube-videos-vlc/">download YouTube videos with VLC</a> or even trim videos with it.</p><p> Another such unusual use of VLC is for screen recording.</p><p> <strong>I still recommend using a proper screen recorder for this task, you are welcome to explore this VLC feature for fun.</strong></p><h2 id="screen-recording-with-vlc"> Screen recording with VLC</h2><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> While I was able to use VLC for recording desktop screen, I could not record any sound and my mouse cursor. In my opinion, it&#39;s not a replacement of a proper screen recording tool.</div></div><p> To record your screen using <a href="https://www.videolan.org/vlc/?ref=itsfoss.com">VLC</a> , open it and click on Media and select Convert/Save. (Or directly click on Media → Open Capture Device) </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/click-on-convert-save.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="979" height="511" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/click-on-convert-save.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/click-on-convert-save.png 979w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Select Convert/ Save option</span></figcaption></figure><p> Go to the &quot;Capture Device&quot; Tab and select Desktop from the Capture Mode dropdown list. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/desktop-in-capture-device.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="929" height="482" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/desktop-in-capture-device.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/desktop-in-capture-device.png 929w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Capture Mode: Desktop</span></figcaption></figure><p> Now, provide some frame rate for your recording. 10, 24 fps etc will be good, and if you need more quality, go for higher. Note that this will increase the file size and system requirements. Then, press the Convert/Save button. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/set-frame-rate-and-press-convert.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="923" height="483" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/set-frame-rate-and-press-convert.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/set-frame-rate-and-press-convert.png 923w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Set Frame Rate</span></figcaption></figure><p> On the next page, select a profile from the drop-down and click on the adjacent button to edit the profile. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-profile-and-edit.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="887" height="518" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Select-profile-and-edit.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Select-profile-and-edit.png 887w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Set Output Profile</span></figcaption></figure><p> Set the Video format you need and press Save. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/profile-settings.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="1158" height="519" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/profile-settings.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/profile-settings.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/profile-settings.png 1158w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Edit the Output Profile</span></figcaption></figure><p> Now, you need to give a destination file name. Click on the Browse button, select a location, and enter the name of the output file. Click Save. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/give-name-to-output-file-and-save.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="1103" height="523" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/give-name-to-output-file-and-save.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/give-name-to-output-file-and-save.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/give-name-to-output-file-and-save.png 1103w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Output file location and Name</span></figcaption></figure><p> Press the Start button, to start recording your screen. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/press-start-button-to-start-recrding.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="1100" height="517" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/press-start-button-to-start-recrding.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/press-start-button-to-start-recrding.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/press-start-button-to-start-recrding.png 1100w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Start Recording</span></figcaption></figure><p> This will start recording. Once you finished your recording, use the panel button to stop. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/stop-button-in-panel-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="904" height="628" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/stop-button-in-panel-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/stop-button-in-panel-1.png 904w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Stop Recording</span></figcaption></figure><p> Or click on the stop button on VLC. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Stop-button-in-VLC.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="938" height="536" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/Stop-button-in-VLC.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/Stop-button-in-VLC.png 938w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Stop Button in VLC</span></figcaption></figure><p> That&#39;s it. You can view the screen recording on the place where you saved it. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/recorded-output.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]" loading="lazy" width="1125" height="464" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/09/recorded-output.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/09/recorded-output.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/09/recorded-output.png 1125w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Output File</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="conclusion">结论</h2><p>As you can see, while it is possible to record the desktop screen with VLC, it is not a replacement of a <a href="https://itsfoss.com/best-linux-screen-recorders/">dedicated screen recording tool</a> . Lack of audio recording is a major letdown.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/best-linux-screen-recorders/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">10 Best Screen Recorders for Linux in 2023</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">Take a look at the best screen recorders available for Linux. Learn its key features, pros, and cons.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Munif Tanjim</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/08/best-screen-recorders.png" alt="How to Record Your Screen with VLC [For Fun]"></div></a></figure><p> Use VLC for screen recording only if you don&#39;t have any other options. What do you think?</p> ; 
How to Add Comments in Bash ScriptsDo you have any comments? Add them to your bash script ;) https://itsfoss.com/bash-comments/ 65156bc1030e5e08c7c1ecfc Bash TipsSagar SharmaTue, 10 Oct 2023 05:41:08 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/add-comments-in-bash-scripts.png" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts"><p> Adding comments in bash scripts is one of the most effective ways to keep your code clean and understandable.</p><p> You may ask why.</p><p> Let&#39;s suppose your script contains a complex regex or multiple complex blocks of codes and in that case, you can add comments so other developers or you can have an idea of what that block of code was meant to be.</p><p> Commenting out part of code also helps in debugging scripts.</p><p> In this tutorial, I will walk you through three ways to add comments in bash scripts:</p><ul><li> Single-line comments</li><li> In line comments</li><li> Multi-line comments</li></ul><p> So let&#39;s start with the first one.</p><h2 id="single-line-comments-in-bash"> Single-line comments in bash</h2><p> To add single-line comments, you have to put the hashtag (#) at the beginning of the line and write a comment.</p><p> Here&#39;s a simple example:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash # This is a comment echo &quot;Hello, World!&quot;</code></pre><p> While executing, the comments will be ignored and when I executed the above command, it looked like this: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-single-line-comments-in-bash.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts" loading="lazy" width="756" height="213" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Use-single-line-comments-in-bash.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-single-line-comments-in-bash.png 756w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-green"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 💡</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> The only exception to the # for comment rule is the #!/bin/bash line at the beginning of the scripts. It&#39;s called <a href="https://linuxhandbook.com/shebang/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">shebang</a> and it used to specify the interpreter to be used while running the script. There are different shells and the syntax may differ. So, a good practice is to specify for which shell the script was written. For example, if it were for ksh, you would use #!/bin/ksh</div></div><h2 id="inline-comments-in-bash-scripts"> Inline comments in bash scripts</h2><p> Alternatively, you can put the comment inside the code block to document what is the purpose of that specific line.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Anything after # won&#39;t be executed until the line ends, so make sure you add the comment at the end of the code.</div></div><p> Here&#39;s a simple example:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash echo &quot;Hello, World!&quot; #Prints hello world</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/How-to-use-the-single-line-comments-in-bash.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts" loading="lazy" width="756" height="196" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/How-to-use-the-single-line-comments-in-bash.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/How-to-use-the-single-line-comments-in-bash.png 756w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h2 id="multi-line-comments-in-bash"> Multi-line comments in bash</h2><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> There is no in-built multiline commenting feature in Bash. However, there are a few workarounds to achieve the multiline comment effect.</div></div><p> As the name suggests, multi-line comments in bash scripting allow you to write comments in multiple lines or prevent executing block of code by putting them in multiline comment section:</p><ol><li> Use # at the begnning of eacj line</li><li> <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3224878/what-is-the-purpose-of-the-colon-gnu-bash-builtin?ref=itsfoss.com">Colon notation</a> (uses colon followed by a single quote)</li><li> Here document (uses &lt;&lt; followed by delimiter)</li></ol><p> So let&#39;s start with the first one.</p><h3 id="1-use-for-each-line-of-block-comment"> 1. Use # for each line of block comment</h3><p> This is what I suggest to use if your purpose is to explain part of the script. After all, # is the actual commenting feature.</p><p> And this is what many developers use, too.</p><p> Suppose you have to explain the purpose of the script, author info or licensing information in the beginning. You can write it like this:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash ###################################### ## This script is used for scanning ## ## local network ## ## Licensed under GPL 2.0 ## ###################################### rest of the bash script code</code></pre><p> That&#39;s fine when you know how your bash script behaves. If you are debugging a bash script and want to hide part of the script, adding # at the beginning of each line of the required code and then removing them after debugging is a time-consuming task.</p><p> The next two sections help you with that.</p><h3 id="2-colon-notation"> 2. Colon notation</h3><p> To use the colon notation, you write block comments between <code>: &#39;</code> and the closing <code>&#39;</code> as shown here:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash : &#39; This is how you can use colon notation And this line too will be ignored &#39; echo &quot;GOODBYE&quot;</code></pre><p> When you execute the above script, it should only print GOODBYE: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-using-colon-notation-in-bash.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts" loading="lazy" width="756" height="287" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-using-colon-notation-in-bash.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-using-colon-notation-in-bash.png 756w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><h3 id="2-here-document"> 2. Here document</h3><p> By far, this is the most popular way to write multiline comments in bash which you use <code>&lt;&lt;</code> followed by a delimiter (a set of characters to specify the start and the end of the comments).</p><p> Here&#39;s how you use it:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash &lt;&lt;DELIMITER Comment line 1 Comment line 2 DELIMITER echo &quot;Hello, World!&quot;</code></pre><p> Still confused? Here&#39;s a simple example:</p><pre> <code>#!/bin/bash &lt;&lt;COMMENT This is a multi-line comment using a here document. You can add as many lines as you want between &lt;&lt;COMMENT and the terminating keyword. This block won&#39;t be executed by the shell. COMMENT echo &quot;Hello, World!&quot;</code></pre><p> In the above example, I have used <code>COMMENT</code> as a delimiter but you can use anything but make sure it stands out from the comment or it will create confusion.</p><p> When I executed the above script, it gave me the following output: </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-in-bash-using----and-delimeter.png" class="kg-image" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts" loading="lazy" width="804" height="321" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-in-bash-using----and-delimeter.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Use-multi-line-comments-in-bash-using----and-delimeter.png 804w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> As you can see, it ignored everything inside &lt;&lt;COMMENT</p><h2 id="learn-bash-from-scratch"> Learn bash from scratch!!</h2><p> If you are planning to learn bash from scratch or want to skim through all the basics, we made a detailed guide for you:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/tag/bash-basics/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Learn Bash Scripting For Free With This Tutorial Series</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">New to bash? Start learning bash scripting with this series in am organized manner. Each chapter also includes sample exercises to practice your learning.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/07/bash-basics.png" alt="How to Add Comments in Bash Scripts"></div></a></figure><p> I hope you will find this guide helpful.</p> ; 
Add Minimize and Maximize Buttons in GNOMEMissing the minimize button option in GNOME? Here's how you can easily bring it back. https://itsfoss.com/gnome-minimize-button/ 652397cb030e5e08c7c2b471 TutorialAbhishek Prakash Mon, 09 Oct 2023 07:09:22 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/add-minimize-and-maximize-buttons-in-gnome.png" alt="Add Minimize and Maximize Buttons in GNOME"><p> Unlike Ubuntu, <a href="https://itsfoss.com/best-fedora-linux-distributions/">distributions like Fedora</a> and Arch Linux give you vanilla GNOME and one thing that may bother you is the lack of minimize and maximize buttons on the application windows. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/missing-minimize-button-gnome.png" class="kg-image" alt="Add Minimize and Maximize Buttons in GNOME" loading="lazy" width="959" height="581" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/missing-minimize-button-gnome.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/missing-minimize-button-gnome.png 959w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">No minimize or maximize button in application windows, only close button</span></figcaption></figure><p> GNOME expects you to use the application switcher (Alt+Tab) or utilize the activities area (Super key) to just switch between running applications, instead of minimizing it.</p><p> The good thing is that you don&#39;t have to live like that if you don&#39;t want it.</p><p> Let me share how you can bring back the minimize and maximize buttons in GNOME using both GUI and command line options.</p><h2 id="method-1-enable-minimize-and-maximize-buttons-using-gnome-tweaks"> Method 1: Enable minimize and maximize buttons using GNOME Tweaks</h2><p> GNOME Tweaks tool allows you customize various aspects of GNOME. Enabling minimize windows buttons is one of them.</p><p> Install GNOME Tweaks tool using your distribution&#39;s package manager first.</p><p> Run the application and go to the Windows Titlebars from the left sidebar. You&#39;ll see the options to add minimize and maximize buttons here, </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/enable-minimize-maximize-windows-option-gnome-tweaks.png" class="kg-image" alt="Add Minimize and Maximize Buttons in GNOME" loading="lazy" width="908" height="499" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/enable-minimize-maximize-windows-option-gnome-tweaks.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/enable-minimize-maximize-windows-option-gnome-tweaks.png 908w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> You can choose either or both. If you don&#39;t want it anymore, <strong>you can disable the buttons the same way in GNOME Tweaks tool</strong> .</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-green"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 💡</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> You can also choose to put these control buttons on the left side if you want. The option is right there at the end of the Titelbar Buttons options.</div></div><h2 id="method-2-use-command-line-to-enable-minimize-and-maximize-buttons"> Method 2: Use command line to enable minimize and maximize buttons</h2><p> The gsettings command has the option to change the button layout and add the minimize and maximize buttons.</p><pre> <code>gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences button-layout &quot;:minimize,maximize,close&quot;</code></pre><p> As you can guess, if you want <strong>to disable any of the buttons, you run the same command but omit the undesired one from the command</strong> .</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-green"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 💡</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> You may also move the windows control buttons to the left by putting the colon in right side in the command:<br> gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences button-layout &quot;close,minimize,maximize:&quot;</div></div><h2 id="getting-inspired-by-macos-is-not-always-a-good-thing"> Getting inspired by macOS is not always a good thing</h2><p> Clearly, this &#39;no minimize button&#39; design is inspired by Apple&#39;s macOS. I remember that around 10 years back, macOS used to have the Windows control on the left. So Ubuntu Unity also tried keeping controls on the left side by default.</p><p> Apple is weird. They have good designs most of the time but they prioritize design over user experience at times. The &#39;magic mouse&#39; is an example. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-embed-card"><div><blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">“Magic Mouse loved by users”. You sure about that? <a href="https://t.co/hxGtTxIrlu?ref=itsfoss.com">pic.twitter.com/hxGtTxIrlu</a></p> — Stuart (@stuwieface) <a href="https://twitter.com/stuwieface/status/1384561367223521286?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&amp;ref=itsfoss.com">April 20, 2021</a> </blockquote><script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script></div></figure><p> I don&#39;t see why GNOME developers have this need of getting inspired by every design, specially the poor ones.</p><p> But that&#39;s just my opinion. I am happy that there exists a quick and easy solution to bring back the minimize and maximize buttons in GNOME.</p> ; 
Ubuntu vs Kubuntu: Which is the Better Choice for You?It can be confusing to pick between Ubuntu and its flavours like Kubuntu. Let's make this task easier. https://itsfoss.com/ubuntu-vs-kubuntu/ 6513b1cd030e5e08c7c16fbd Distro War ⚔️Ankush Das Sat, 07 Oct 2023 03:30:40 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ubuntu-vs-kubuntu.png" alt="Ubuntu vs Kubuntu: Which is the Better Choice for You?"><p> Ubuntu is the most popular Linux distribution for desktop users. It features a customized GNOME desktop to provide a seamless user experience. Exciting</p><p> On the other hand, Kubuntu is one of the <a href="https://itsfoss.com/which-ubuntu-install/" rel="noreferrer">Ubuntu flavours</a> featuring the <strong>KDE Plasma desktop</strong> .</p><p> At its core, both distributions are similar, with the <a href="https://itsfoss.com/what-is-desktop-environment/" rel="noreferrer">desktop environment</a> as the striking difference.</p><p> <em>What exactly are the differences? Is one of them better than the other? What is the perfect distro for your use-case?</em></p><p> Here, we shall highlight the key differences along with essentials to help you pick one.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> This comparison uses Ubuntu 23.04 and Kubuntu 23.04. With future releases, there can be some differences, which we will be regularly updating.</div></div><h2 id="desktop-environments"> Desktop Environments</h2><p> Ubuntu features a customized look using the <a href="https://www.gnome.org/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">GNOME</a> desktop. The layout is unique for new Linux users, and yet easy to use. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ubuntu-23-04-home-with-wallpaper.jpg" class="kg-image" alt="Ubuntu vs Kubuntu: Which is the Better Choice for You?" loading="lazy" width="1266" height="765" srcset="https://it