> or the <strong>Ubuntu App Center</strong> (in newer versions starting from <a href="https://news.itsfoss.com/ubuntu-23-10/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">Ubuntu 23.10</a> ), which includes Snap integration by default. So, if you prefer using Snaps over Flatpak, Ubuntu can give you a seamless experience installing them. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ubuntu-softwar-center-app.png" class="kg-image" alt="Ubuntu vs Kubuntu: Which is the Better Choice for You?" loading="lazy" width="1144" height="761" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/ubuntu-softwar-center-app.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/ubuntu-softwar-center-app.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/ubuntu-softwar-center-app.png 1144w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> To use packages from Flathub, you can follow our <a href="https://itsfoss.com/flatpak-guide/" rel="noreferrer">guide on using Flatpak</a> , but there are no baked in integration options with Ubuntu&#39;s software manager.</p><p> When it comes to Kubuntu, you get &quot; <strong>Discover</strong> &quot; as the software manager. You get applications from the repositories and Snap packages as well. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/kde-discover.png" class="kg-image" alt="Ubuntu vs Kubuntu: Which is the Better Choice for You?" loading="lazy" width="1066" height="843" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/kde-discover.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/kde-discover.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/kde-discover.png 1066w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p> Compared to Ubuntu&#39;s software store, Discover is a bit <strong>more flexible with an available add-on to easily integrate Flatpak</strong> .</p><p> All you need is a few clicks to list apps from Flathub on 